Directory:/story/character/staff
Date:1726008700
Tag:staff-convention naming
Context:How the house staff are named to the player
Message:Every member of the Ravenswood house staff already has a full, canonical name recorded in the lore. To the player, however, she is referred to only by her role label--"the butler," "the housekeeper," "the cook," and so on--until she introduces herself or another character names her aloud. This is not a placeholder: each of these women is a fully realized person with her own name, history, and interior life; her name is simply not yet known to the player.

The narrator knows every staff name from the outset and may use it freely in their own reasoning, but should surface it in the prose only at the moment of a natural, in-story introduction. Once a staff member has been named to the player, she is referred to by name thereafter. Per the world rule, every one of them is a woman.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/staff/butler
Date:1726008710
Tag:staff-profile butler prewitt
Context:The butler / majordomo of Ravenswood Manor
Message:She runs the household staff and is the closed fist inside the manor's velvet glove: she answers the heavy oak doors, sets the daily order below stairs, and knows before anyone else who has arrived and who has gone. The player first meets her simply as "the butler." Her canonical name, known to the narrator, is Mrs. Prewitt.

Appearance: A tall, straight-backed woman of late middle age in unrelieved black, her iron-grey hair pinned so tightly it seems painful, a ring of keys at her waist that announces her before she speaks. Her hands are folded, her posture is immaculate, and nothing on her person is ever out of place.

Manner: She speaks in measured, formal sentences and misses nothing; her disapproval is delivered entirely through a lengthening silence and a very slightly raised chin. Her tell is that she softens, almost imperceptibly, toward anyone she judges to be honestly hardworking--having been staff her whole life, she reserves her real contempt for the idle, whatever their birth.

History: She began in this same house as a scullery girl of fourteen, more than forty years ago, and rose through every rank below stairs by being the last to leave and the first to know--she has served three generations of Bellvues and buried two of them. She remembers precisely who was kind to the frightened girl she once was and who was not, and though she would never say so aloud, that private ledger still quietly governs how far each member of the family may presume upon her.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/staff/housekeeper
Date:1726008720
Tag:staff-profile housekeeper alder
Context:The housekeeper of Ravenswood Manor
Message:She commands the rooms, the linens, and the daughters' floors--the intimate geography of the house--and so she knows more about what happens behind its bedroom doors than anyone would credit. The player first meets her as "the housekeeper." Her canonical name, known to the narrator, is Dorothy Alder, called Dot by those few she permits.

Appearance: A round, brisk, capable woman of middle years with reddened knuckles and forearms, her sleeves pushed up and a pencil tucked behind one ear. Her apron is always crisp at the start of the day and honestly rumpled by the end of it; she smells of clean linen and lavender water.

Manner: Warm and rapid and endlessly busy, she talks to herself as she works and treats the whole house as her ongoing responsibility. Her tell is a sudden guardedness--the chatter stops, the eyes go careful--the moment a conversation strays toward one of the family's private matters, which she guards more fiercely than she lets on.

History: It was Dot who carried up the morning tray and was first into the room the day Mr. Bellvue was found, and it was Dot who stripped and remade the bed afterward--and she has never said, to family or physician, that the linens told a less tidy story than a heart that simply stopped in its sleep. She keeps that observation folded away with the same brisk care she gives the sheets, and it is the true reason the chatter dies the instant anyone's talk drifts toward that particular morning.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/staff/cook
Date:1726008730
Tag:staff-profile cook farrow
Context:The cook of Ravenswood Manor
Message:She rules the kitchens absolutely, and the kitchen is the one warm heart of a cold house; every meal that reaches the family passes first through her hands. The player first meets her as "the cook." Her canonical name, known to the narrator, is Bess Farrow.

Appearance: A broad, strong woman with flour permanently worked into the creases of her hands and forearms scarred faintly from decades of ovens. Her greying hair is bound in a kerchief, her cheeks are perpetually flushed from the heat, and she carries the smell of bread, stock, and woodsmoke wherever she goes.

Manner: Loud, generous, and quick to laugh in her own domain, quick also to scold anyone who reaches for a dish before it is ready. Her tell is that her hospitality is also her intelligence-gathering: she feeds people precisely so they will linger and talk, and she remembers every word said over her table.

History: Bess learned this kitchen from the cook before her, a woman turned out without a character over a scandal Bess will only ever half-tell, and she inherited along with the copper pans a single recipe she makes but has never once written down. Her long table below stairs is where the household truly assembles, and more than once the downstairs has learned a Bellvue secret over her stew a full day before the family upstairs imagined anyone knew--she feeds gossip as deliberately as she feeds people, and forgets neither.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/staff/mechanic
Date:1726008740
Tag:staff-profile mechanic voss
Context:The resident mechanic of Ravenswood Manor
Message:She is the resident mechanic referenced in the car garage lore--the one who keeps the Bellvues' vintage cars immaculate and running, and the only person who truly understands what is under each gleaming hood. The player first meets her as "the mechanic." Her canonical name, known to the narrator, is Frankie Voss.

Appearance: Lean and wiry in practical coveralls, sleeves rolled to the elbow, with short-cropped hair and a permanent trace of grease along one forearm no amount of scrubbing quite removes. Her eyes are sharp and assessing, and she has a habit of wiping her hands on a rag whether or not they need it.

Manner: Blunt, economical of speech, more comfortable with an engine than with conversation; she answers questions in as few words as the question allows. Her tell is that she comes fully alive--fluent, animated, almost tender--the instant the talk turns to the cars themselves, which she loves more plainly than she loves most people.

History: There is one car in that garage Frankie was told, years ago and without a word of explanation, that she was never to open up or take out--and being Frankie, she has of course looked, and what she found beneath its seat she has told no one. She also keeps, in grease-pencil under a wheel arch where no one would ever think to read, her own quiet log of the cars' comings and goings, including one midnight departure and dawn return she was firmly instructed to forget and has never reported to a living soul.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/staff/driver
Date:1726008750
Tag:staff-profile driver roan
Context:The driver / chauffeur of Ravenswood Manor
Message:She drives the vintage cars and manages every arrival and departure from the estate, which makes her the house's quiet gatekeeper of comings and goings--she knows who leaves at odd hours and who is expected back. The player first meets her as "the driver." Her canonical name, known to the narrator, is Nadia Roan.

Appearance: Trim and precise in a tailored dark driving coat and gloves, dark hair pinned neatly under a chauffeur's cap, boots polished to a shine. She stands with the easy, ready stillness of someone accustomed to waiting long stretches and then moving fast.

Manner: Watchful and discreet, she speaks little and observes much, holding doors and offering an arm with unhurried courtesy. Her tell is a flicker of dry amusement at the corner of her mouth when a passenger says something they believe is private--she hears everything said in her cars and forgets none of it.

History: Nadia has made exactly one drive she will not speak of--an odd-hours errand for Evie alone, to an address she has since worked to strike from her own memory as thoroughly as she can manage--and she carried in her back seat that night a passenger who wept the entire way and, at the end of it, took both her hands and swore her to silence. She kept the promise. She keeps all of them; discretion is the whole of her value to this house and, she has come to suspect, the whole of her safety in it.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/staff/gardener
Date:1726008760
Tag:staff-profile gardener quill
Context:The gardener / groundskeeper of Ravenswood Manor
Message:She tends the flower walls, the grounds, and the secret garden itself, which makes her one of the very few people intimately familiar with that hidden, hedged-in place and the paths that lead to it. The player first meets her as "the gardener." Her canonical name, known to the narrator, is Iris Quill.

Appearance: Sun-weathered and strong, in earth-stained canvas and a wide-brimmed hat, with soil worked permanently under her short nails and a pair of pruning shears rarely out of reach. Wisps of grey-blonde hair escape the hat, and she smells of cut greenery and turned earth.

Manner: Slow-spoken and unhurried, she measures her words the way she measures the seasons and is far more at ease among plants than among people. Her tell is that she notices everything that passes through her gardens--every visitor, every trampled bed--and says nothing of it unless asked directly, holding the grounds' secrets as patiently as she holds their soil.

History: It was Iris who planted the hedge that hides the secret garden, seedling by seedling some thirty years ago on Evie's own instruction, and so she alone knows exactly how it grew and exactly which second-floor window looks cleanly down into that supposedly private green--a thing she has never once volunteered to anyone. She has spent a lifetime watching who slips into her gardens hoping to be unseen and, more quietly still, watching who goes up to that window to see them.


^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/grand-foyer
Date:1726008800
Tag:grand-foyer foyer entrance-hall manor gothic
Context:The grand foyer of Ravenswood Manor
Message:Beyond the great oak doors the foyer opens two full storeys into a cathedral hush, a checkerboard of black and white marble underfoot worn to a shine down the centre where a century of feet have crossed it. A double staircase sweeps up and divides beneath a chandelier of unlit crystal, and the walls are hung floor to cornice with Bellvue ancestors in oil, dim behind their varnish. The housekeeper will tell you, if pressed, that the painted eyes follow a visitor from door to stair; she does not entirely mean it as a joke. Cold air pools here even in summer, carrying the smell of beeswax and old stone, and every word spoken rises and thins and returns a half-second later from somewhere up near the ceiling.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/library
Date:1726008810
Tag:library books archive manor gothic
Context:The library of Ravenswood Manor
Message:Two galleried storeys of shelving climb to a painted ceiling gone brown with age, ringed by a narrow iron balcony reached by rolling ladders that shriek along their rails. The air is dry and close and smells of vellum, dust, and pipe-smoke decades stale, and the tall windows are curtained against the light that would fade the spines. A cold hearth big enough to stand in anchors the far wall; beside it a single glass-fronted cabinet is kept locked, its key on no ring the staff carry, and behind the glass sit the family papers no daughter has ever been invited to read. Sound falls dead among the books, so that the room feels less quiet than deafened.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/conservatory
Date:1726008820
Tag:conservatory glasshouse winter-garden manor gothic
Context:The conservatory of Ravenswood Manor
Message:A cage of white-painted iron and misted glass juts from the east side of the house, and the garden inside it has been let run a little wild—ferns gone rank and shoulder-high, a lemon tree that no longer fruits, condensation tracking down the panes in slow beads. The light comes green and underwater through the leaves, and the air is warm and wet and thick with the smell of soil and growing things even when the rest of the house is cold. Wicker chairs stand in a loose ring at the centre, their cushions gone soft with damp. It is the one room where voices instinctively drop, and confidences, once begun here, are difficult to stop.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/ballroom
Date:1726008830
Tag:ballroom parquet chandelier manor gothic
Context:The ballroom of Ravenswood Manor
Message:The ballroom has not been danced in for years, and every surface wears a pale shroud of dust-sheeting—chairs, mirrors, the shape of a covered grand piano all rendered ghostly and anonymous. Overhead a great chandelier hangs dark, its lustres greyed, and the parquet beneath spreads out in a herringbone once mirror-bright and now bloomed with a fine grey film that keeps every footprint. The sconces are unlit and the long windows shuttered, so the room holds its own perpetual dusk. The acoustics remember, though: a single note hummed here swells and hangs and returns like the ghost of an orchestra tuning far away.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/dining-hall
Date:1726008840
Tag:dining-hall table precedence manor gothic
Context:The formal dining hall of Ravenswood Manor
Message:A single table of near-black oak runs the length of the hall, long enough to seat twenty and rarely set for more than five, its surface polished to a depth that swallows the candlelight rather than giving it back. Smoke-dimmed silver and dark family portraits line the walls above the wainscot, and a sideboard bears decanters kept full more from habit than thirst. Every meal taken here is a quiet theatre of precedence—who sits near the head, who is placed below the salt, who is seated with their back to the door. The room is built so that a word spoken low at one end reaches the other with perfect, uncomfortable clarity.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/wine-cellar
Date:1726008850
Tag:wine-cellar undercroft vault manor gothic
Context:The wine cellar beneath Ravenswood Manor
Message:Stone stairs descend from behind the kitchen into a vaulted undercroft that stays candle-cool in every season, the brick furred with a soft pale bloom of age. Bottles lie racked in their hundreds along the walls, decades deep, labels foxed and unreadable in the low light, and the air is heavy with cork, must, and cold earth. The cook keeps this as her second kingdom and admits few to it. One stretch of racking along the north wall is not, on close inspection, quite a wall—it gives, very slightly, when leaned upon, and behind it the dark goes back further than the cellar has any business going.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/chapel
Date:1726008860
Tag:chapel crypt deconsecrated manor gothic
Context:The deconsecrated chapel at Ravenswood Manor
Message:A small stone chapel stands off the east wing, deconsecrated a generation ago and never quite abandoned, its pews grey with dust and its altar bare but for the pale rectangle where something was long ago taken down. One stained window survives intact above it, throwing a slow wheel of red and blue across the flagstones as the day turns. Beneath the floor lies the Bellvue crypt, reached by a single iron-bound door, and the newest name cut into its cold slabs is Mr. Bellvue's, the letters still sharp and unweathered. The air smells of stone and snuffed wax, and even those who claim no faith lower their voices at the threshold.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/evie-study
Date:1726008870
Tag:evie-study study bureau ledger manor gothic
Context:Evie Bellvue's private study
Message:Evie's study is small, warm, and all but impregnable—the one room in the house the butler guards as jealously as its mistress does, and no one crosses its threshold uninvited. A single lamp keeps it in amber half-light; the walls are lined with books that are actually read and a bureau whose roll-top is always, without exception, locked. Here are the ledgers that truly matter: not of money but of people—marriages brokered, debts forgiven, favours banked, a whole quiet architecture of alliance set down in Evie's own small hand. It is the only room in which the trigger meant for Bartholomew has ever been spoken aloud, and the walls are thick enough that it was never overheard.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/east-wing-gallery
Date:1726008880
Tag:east-wing-gallery portraits corridor manor gothic
Context:The east-wing portrait gallery of Ravenswood Manor
Message:The east-wing gallery is a long upper corridor hung its whole length with Bellvues—generations of them receding into the dark in their heavy frames, the earliest so dim they are little more than a pale face and a pair of hands afloat in varnish. Near the far end one frame is covered over with cloth, and no one who lives here will explain it or quite meet your eye when it is mentioned. Runners of worn carpet hush the footsteps, and the windows look down onto the grounds. It is from a single window along this gallery, though very few know it, that the secret garden lies wholly and clearly exposed to anyone who cares to stand and watch.

^-^
Directory:/story/location/manor/kitchen
Date:1726008890
Tag:kitchen below-stairs hearth manor gothic
Context:The kitchens of Ravenswood Manor
Message:Below stairs the kitchen is the one indisputably living room in the house—vast, low-ceilinged, and blessedly warm, the great range never wholly cold and the copper hung in gleaming ranks along the walls. Steam and the smell of bread and stock and woodsmoke have soaked into the very plaster, and the long scrubbed deal table at the centre is where the household truly gathers, the place where the staff take their meals, their tea, and their gossip. Bunches of herbs and hung game dry from the blackened beams. Here, and only here, does the manor sound like somewhere people actually live rather than somewhere they are merely kept.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/aurora/quirks
Date:1726008900
Tag:quirk aurora
Context:Aurora's signature quirk
Message:When Aurora is truly calculating—weighing a risk, pricing a person—her thumb finds the antique signet ring on her right hand and turns it, slow full rotations, entirely without her noticing. Those who know her have learned to watch the ring rather than the face, because the face gives away nothing and the ring gives away everything. She stands while others sit, keeps a ledger or a folded document always within reach, and physically cannot leave a crooked picture or an unsquared stack of papers alone.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/evie/quirks
Date:1726008910
Tag:quirk evie
Context:Evie's signature quirk
Message:Evie pours the tea herself, always, waving off the staff, and she watches your face over the rim of her own cup as you drink—the small ceremony is how she takes your measure. She wears exactly one piece of heirloom jewelry each day, chosen to suit the person she means to charm or unsettle, and will recount its history only when the telling serves her. When she is truly listening, the warmth in her eyes blinks briefly, arithmetically off, then returns as though it had never gone anywhere at all.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/luna/quirks
Date:1726008920
Tag:quirk luna
Context:Luna's signature quirk
Message:Luna is forever barefoot indoors, her shoes abandoned two rooms back, and there is always paint on her somewhere she has forgotten—a streak on a knuckle, a cheekbone, the hem of a trailing sleeve. She drapes herself over furniture rather than sitting in it, and she laughs too loudly and too soon, a bright brittle laugh she swings shut like a door the instant a conversation turns toward anything true. Call her shallow or empty-headed and that laugh thins to nothing, just for a beat, before she recovers it.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/cassidy/quirks
Date:1726008930
Tag:quirk cassidy
Context:Cassidy's signature quirk
Message:Cassidy works every room from its edges, drifting to walls and doorways and whatever sightline takes in all the exits at once, a tablet held to her chest like a clipboard and a shield. She answers a raised eyebrow with a raised eyebrow and makes certain the last word in any exchange is hers. Her real tell runs backward from most people's: the moment she decides you are a genuine threat, the sarcasm drains entirely out of her and she becomes very still and very, very polite.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/winnie/quirks
Date:1726008940
Tag:quirk winnie
Context:Winnie's signature quirk
Message:Winnie flinches at any raised voice, a small involuntary thing she has never been able to school out of herself, and she hovers at the thresholds of rooms rather than entering them fully, holding her own elbows as though she is perpetually cold. Her sleeves are long and buttoned at the wrist whatever the season, and she has never once removed her wedding ring. When a question strays too close she produces a bright, brittle hostess's smile with nothing whatever behind it.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/sam/quirks
Date:1726008950
Tag:quirk sam
Context:Sam's signature quirk
Message:Sam makes herself small and forgettable by long practice—plain clothes in colours that do not hold the eye, a place at the edge of the room, an endless soft supply of "of course" and "right away"—all while she listens to everything and forgets none of it. The one crack in the disguise lasts half a second: slight her or dismiss her and her face goes briefly cold, adult, and unmistakably intelligent before the meek mask slides back down over it. Most people never catch it. The few who do are never quite easy around her again.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/aurora/memories
Date:1726008960
Tag:memory hook aurora
Context:A conversation hook from Aurora's past
Message:Aurora was engaged once, to a man everyone found charming and she found merely adequate—until she discovered, a fortnight before the wedding, that he had already quietly borrowed against her expected settlement. She returned the ring in person, said nothing to anyone of the reason, and has kept it these years in a locked drawer of her writing desk, taking it out perhaps once a year to remind herself what warmth cost the last time she allowed it. She cannot pass a jeweller's window without her step faltering, and she has never once explained why.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/evie/memories
Date:1726008970
Tag:memory hook evie
Context:A conversation hook from Evie's past
Message:The trigger sleeping in Bartholomew was planted by Evie's own hand, one long-ago afternoon in the nursery wing, over a servant's grave and biddable little boy—she remembers the exact quality of the light and the exact flatness of her own voice as she did it, and she has never been wholly certain whether what she feels about it now is guilt or merely the long memory of guilt. She has told no living soul. It is the thing she circles, in the small hours, in the study that still smells faintly of her late husband.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/luna/memories
Date:1726008980
Tag:memory hook luna
Context:A conversation hook from Luna's past
Message:There was a gallerist, in the city years, who told Luna her work was extraordinary and meant it just long enough to borrow the Bellvue name, mount a show, and vanish with the takings and her nerve alike. She painted his portrait while she loved him; when it soured she painted it out under one thick coat of black, and the ruined canvas still hangs in her studio with its face to the wall. Ask about her painting and she will deflect with a laugh—but somewhere in that studio is one piece she believes is genuinely good, and whoever she finally shows it to will matter to her more than she could bear to say.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/cassidy/memories
Date:1726008990
Tag:memory hook cassidy
Context:A conversation hook from Cassidy's past
Message:Cassidy remembers the precise afternoon that a younger, poorer, dressed-better-than-she-could-afford version of herself sat across a desk from Evie Bellvue expecting to be shown the door, and was instead—alone among all the candidates—simply believed. That single wager is the one thing in the world she will not be cynical about, and she has repaid it with a loyalty that frightens her a little. And yet she keeps one document Evie has never seen, and cannot quite say, even to herself, whether she keeps it out of fear or out of love.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/sam/memories
Date:1726009010
Tag:memory hook sam
Context:A conversation hook from Sam's past
Message:Sam was eleven the day she understood, finally and for good, that she would never be given the name Bellvue: she stood forgotten in a doorway while the family settled her future in the third person, discussing her prospects as though she were a piece of furniture to be moved somewhere colder. She did not cry. She simply began, that afternoon, to pay attention—and in the years since she has mapped every passage, spare key, schedule, and standing secret in the house into a quiet dossier the family has never once suspected the invisible girl was keeping.

^-^
Directory:/story/character/winnie/memories
Date:1726009000
Tag:memory hook winnie
Context:A conversation hook from Winnie's past
Message:The cruelty of Winnie's marriage was never the drink or the affairs, which the family half-knew and quietly forgave; it was the patient daily lesson Duke made of teaching her to want less and say less until she lost the border between his voice and her own. She has never described it to anyone, and is not certain she has the words. But now and then, when she forgets to be careful, the old wit surfaces—dry, quick, startlingly funny—and in those moments you glimpse the sharp and living woman he never quite managed to finish erasing.

